  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_323923913" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/323923913" />
    <a title="Elaine" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1381943-elaine"><img alt="Elaine" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442502831p2/1381943.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/323923913?book_show_action=true">May 04, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elaine" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elaine" href="/user/show/1381943-elaine">Elaine</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer323923913" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13066842250303421365">Reading this with two GoodReads friends -- which is probably the only way I am going to get through it. I have only read a few dozen pages and (silly me -- looking for paragraph breaks) keep getting lost in the curtains and the grandmother&apos;s affections.<br/>Finally finished this -- finally. Now I realize that getting lost in thoughts about the curtains, the hawthorne bushes and his mother&apos;s lace hems is probably the point. Still, I got impatient. I found the first part of Combray quite tiresome, enou</span>
  <span id="freeText13066842250303421365" style="display:none">Reading this with two GoodReads friends -- which is probably the only way I am going to get through it. I have only read a few dozen pages and (silly me -- looking for paragraph breaks) keep getting lost in the curtains and the grandmother's affections.<br />Finally finished this -- finally. Now I realize that getting lost in thoughts about the curtains, the hawthorne bushes and his mother's lace hems is probably the point. Still, I got impatient. I found the first part of Combray quite tiresome, enough with the whiny little boy. The early parts of Swann in Love were terrific, evocative insight on what it's like to be loved by someone whom you love a little less, then how it feels when the tables are turned and the other person loves you less than you love her, and all the excuses and rationales and bizarre behavior you (Swann) are capable of just to win or woo or not be totally destroyed by your lover. But this too went on and on, like a 19th C. Portnoy and I got tired of it too. But then came the pay-off: Place-Names: The Name brought the delightful innocence of the young boy together with a love story that paralleled Swann's roller coaster love story, and that was a delicious read. <br />I did relish being immersed in Paris, and the surprising humor, and some amazing language, and the reverie on reading. But not enough to read another volume. <br />....on second thought. This is I realized after bumping into a friend, a journalist, on the street and both of us bewailing the kinds of instant "journalism" that surrounds us now, where we learn everything so quickly, and probably forget it just as quickly to make room for the next instant news item -- from world-shaking events to celebrity split-ups. She was advised to read poetry before writing her next news story. And I was holding on to my Proust, and realized that Swann's Way -- though sometimes exasperating -- did make me slow down, see the pathways in Combray, every leaf, every whiff of lemon-flower tea, every shade of purple. And that kind of slow observation and recording is so valuable, as much in our world as in his -- or maybe even more. Just wanted to add that....<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="13066842250303421365" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

